genealogical relationships between these are established on the basis of separative and conjunctive errors, identified, inter alia, through critical discussions of more than 300 passages. The second part of the introduction discusses the nature, purpose and sources of the paraphrases as well as several linguistic questions with implications for editing and translating the text. The third part of the introduction sets out the principles of this edition and translation.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aAristoteles-Kommentare. 4aByzantinische Hochsprache. 4aByzantinische Philosophie.  aByzantine 'Hochsprache'.  aByzantine philosophy.  acommentaries on Aristotle.1 aBydén, Börje, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt0 cprintz978311078602640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311078606440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110786064423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110786064/original  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK